'''"Kid"''' is a song written by [[Chrissie Hynde]] that was released on [[the Pretenders]] 1980 debut album ''[[Pretenders (album)|Pretenders]]''.  It was also released as a single and reached #33 in the UK. It has been covered by several other artists, including [[Everything but the Girl]].

==Background==
Author Alex Ogg describes "Kid" as a "resonant [[ballad]]."<ref name=rough>{{cite book|title=The Rough Guide to Rock|author=Ogg. A.|editor=Buckley, P.|pages=814-815|year=2003|publisher=Rough Guides|isbn= 9781843531050}}</ref>  The lyrics express the singer's devotion to the listener, who may be her child, but could also be her lover or just a friend.<ref name=allmusic>{{cite web|title=Kid|author=Mason, S.|url=http://www.allmusic.com/song/kid-mt0029950215|publisher=[[Allmusic]]|accessdate=2014-05-04}}</ref>  [[Allmusic]] critic Stewart Mason calls it "an all-time classic [[rock and roll]] love song" and "probably the [Pretenders]' masterpiece."<ref name=allmusic/>  He particularly praises Hynde's "beautiful and emotional" lead vocals, and [[James Honeyman-Scott]]'s [[lead guitar]] playing, which he says sounds like [[the Byrds]] at times but also sounds tougher when necessary.<ref name=allmusic/>  Allmusic critic [[Stephen Thomas Erlewine]] also praised how Honeyman-Scott's "unconventional" playing adds additional dimensions to the "measured pop" of "Kid."<ref>{{cite web|title=Pretenders|author=[[Stephen Thomas Erlewine|Erlewine, S.T.]]|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/pretenders-mw0000387388|publisher=[[Allmusic]]|accessdate=2014-05-04}}</ref>  Author Jeremy Simmonds said of "Kid" that it "showed the group's complete mastery of sixties hooks with sharp. confident [[new wave music|new wave]] leanings."<ref>{{cite book|title=The Encyclopedia of Dead Rock Stars: Heroin, Handguns, and Ham Sandwiches|author=Simmonds, J.|page=165|year=2008|publisher=Chicago Review Press|isbn= 9781556527548}}</ref>  ''[[Rolling Stone Album Guide]]'' critic J.D. Considine praises how [[melody]] expresses "emotional vulnerability."<ref name=guide>{{cite book|title=[[The Rolling Stone Album Guide]]|author=Considine, J.D.|editor=DeCurtis, A. |editor2=Henke, J. |editor3=George-Warren, H.|pages=232-233|year=1992|publisher=Straight Arrow Publishers|edition=3rd|isbn=0679737294}}</ref>  Considine also praises how the band adds "soul" to the song's "sentimentality."<ref name=guide/>  According to Mason, the Pretenders' later single "[[Show Me (Pretenders song)|Show Me]]" was partially a rewrite of "Kid."<ref>{{cite web|title=Show Me|author=Mason, S.|url=http://www.allmusic.com/song/show-me-mt0011842597|publisher=[[Allmusic]]|accessdate=2014-05-04}}</ref>

"Kid" was released as the Pretenders' second single in 1979, prior to the release of their debut album, following "[[Stop Your Sobbing]]."  It performed slightly better on the UK charts than "Stop Your Sobbing," reaching #33 whereas "Stop Your Sobbing" reached #34.<ref name=ukchart>{{cite web|title=Pretenders UK singles|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/artist/_/pretenders/|publisher=[[The Official Charts Company]]|accessdate=2014-05-04}}</ref>  However, the band's follow up single "[[Brass in Pocket]]" performed even better, reaching #1.<ref name=ukchart/>

Since its original release, "Kid" has appeared on a number of Pretenders' compilation albums. including ''[[The Singles (Pretenders album)|The Singles]]'' and ''[[Greatest Hits (Pretenders album)|Greatest Hits]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Singles|author=Greenwald, M.|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/the-singles-mw0000197989|publisher=[[Allmusic]]|accessdate=2014-05-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Greatest Hits|author=Prato, G,|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/greatest-hits-mw0000461818|publisher=[[Allmusic]]|accessdate=2014-05-04}}</ref>  It also appears on the live album ''[[The Isle of View]]'', in which Hynde is backed by a [[string quartet]], in what [[Stephen Thomas Erlewine]] describes as a "poorly conceived" version.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Isle of View|author=[[Stephen Thomas Erlewine|Erlewine, S.T.]]|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/the-isle-of-view-mw0000179840|publisher=[[Allmusic]]|accessdate=2014-05-04}}</ref>

==Cover versions==
[[Everything but the Girl]] covered "Kid" on the US version of their 1985 album ''[[Love Not Money]]'', with [[Tracey Thorn]] playing piano and singing solo vocal.<ref name=allmusic/><ref name=love/>  Allmusic's Mason praised this as the best cover version of "Kid."<ref name=allmusic/>  However, fellow Allmusic critic William Ruhlmann claimed that adding the song to the US version did not enhance the album's appeal.<ref name=love>{{cite web|title=Love Not Money|author=Ruhlmann, W.|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/love-not-money-mw0000318569|publisher=[[Allmusic]]|accessdate=2014-05-04}}</ref>

Though not a cover, [[Local H]] featured "The One With 'Kid'" as the leading song on their album [[12 Angry Months]].  The Pretenders songs is notably mentioned in the lyrics.

